[2]
Date: Sat 10 Feb 2018
From: Allen Lenoir <alenoir165@aol.com> [edited]


Has the cause of the meningitis in the 39-year-old in Spain been determined, and is more known about the patient? _Listeria_ would seem to be less likely in a patient this age unless they were immunocompromised. A more likely cause of meningitis related to the consumption of unpasteurized cheese in an immunocompetent 39 year old would be _Brucella_.

--
Allen Lenoir, MD
Miami, Florida
<alenoir165@aol.com>

[ProMED-mail thanks Irene Lai and Allen Lenoir for providing their contributions.

Dr Lenoir is correct. As I stated in my moderator comments (see 20180209.5618781), listeriosis affects mainly pregnant women, newborns, the elderly, and adults with impaired immune systems. Invasive disease, like meningitis, due to _Listeria monocytogenes_ would be uncommon in an immune competent 39-year-old man, but certainly invasive disease in apparently immunocompetent non-elderly adults has been reported (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6428282, https://ojs.library.dal.ca/DMJ/article/download/3793/3465, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5771898/, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22760149, https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/0b1e/3e311e79f55e4e80c82eee5a4c9512cea0a1.pdf).

More information on the 39-year old man in Madrid who developed _Listeria_ meningitis would be appreciated from knowledgeable sources.

A map of Spain can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5621382,43 and of Portugal at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5621382,42. - Mod.ML]
